specJson.label: Random Forest Classification Train
specJson.description:
Random forest classification model is an ensemble learning method that operates by constructing a multitude of decision trees at training time and outputting the class that is the mode of the individual trees. Random forest model corrects for decision trees' habit of overfitting to their training set. 

Different kinds of models have different advantages. Random forest model is very good at handling tabular data with numerical features, or categorical features with fewer than hundreds of categories. Unlike linear models, random forests are able to capture non-linear interaction between the features and the target.

Reference: 
+ <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_forest>
+ <https://turi.com/learn/userguide/supervised-learning/random_forest_regression.html>

params.description: The column designated for the labels of data. The column should contain categorical type values as it is for classification.

params.label: Number of Trees
params.description: Controls the number of trees in the final model. If 1, then no bootstrapping is used. If > 1, then bootstrapping will be performed. Usually the more trees, the higher accuracy. However, both the training and prediction time also grows linearly in the number of trees.

params.label: Feature Selection Criterion
params.description: The function to measure the quality of a split.

params.label: Maximum Depth
params.description: The maximum depth of the tree. It restricts the depth of each individual tree to prevent overfitting. If None, then nodes are expanded until all leaves are pure or until all leaves contain less than `Minimum Number of Samples to Split`.

params.label: Minimum Number of Samples to Split
params.description: The minimum number of samples required to split an internal node. A very small number will usually mean the tree will overfit, whereas a large number will prevent the tree from learning the data.

params.label: Minimum Number of Samples in a Leaf
params.description: The minimum number of samples required to be at a leaf node. A split point at any depth will only be considered if it leaves at least `Minimum Number of Samples in a Leaf` training samples in each of the left and right branches. This may have the effect of smoothing the model, especially in regression. While `Minimum Number of Samples to Split` can create arbitrarily small leaves, `Minimum Number of Samples in a Leaf` guarantees that each leaf has a minimum size, avoiding low-variance, over-fit leaf nodes in regression problems.

params.label: Number of Features
params.description: The number of features to consider when looking for the best split.

params.label: Class Weights
params.description: Weights associated with classes. If weights are not given, all classes are supposed to have weight one. Note that the class labels are considered in lexicographical order and the number of Class Weights should match number of labels.

params.label: Seed
params.description: Random seed. Use the same seed in order to reproduce the same results.

specJson.summary: This function trains a random forest model for classification.

md:
# Random Forest Classification Train This function trains a random forest model for classification. ## Description Random forest classification model is an ensemble learning method that operates by constructing a multitude of decision trees at training time and outputting the class that is the mode of the individual trees. Random forest model corrects for decision trees' habit of overfitting to their training set. Different kinds of models have different advantages. Random forest model is very good at handling tabular data with numerical features, or categorical features with fewer than hundreds of categories. Unlike linear models, random forests are able to capture non-linear interaction between the features and the target. Reference: + + ## Properties ### VA #### INPUT 1. **table***: (Table) Training data in a Table. It must contain at least one column for labels. #### OUTPUT 1. **model**:(Model) Random Forest Classification model. #### PARAMETER 1. **Feature Columns***: Feature column names. Only values in numeric type are possible. 2. **Label Column***: The column designated for the labels of data. The column should contain categorical type values as it is for classification. 3. **Number of Trees**: Controls the number of trees in the final model. If 1, then no bootstrapping is used. If > 1, then bootstrapping will be performed. Usually the more trees, the higher accuracy. However, both the training and prediction time also grows linearly in the number of trees. - Available Options : `Gini Impurity`, `Entropy` 4. **Feature Selection Criterion**: The function to measure the quality of a split. 5. **Maximum Depth**: The maximum depth of the tree. It restricts the depth of each individual tree to prevent overfitting. If None, then nodes are expanded until all leaves are pure or until all leaves contain less than `Minimum Number of Samples to Split`. 6. **Minimum Number of Samples to Split**: The minimum number of samples required to split an internal node. A very small number will usually mean the tree will overfit, whereas a large number will prevent the tree from learning the data. 7. **Minimum Number of Samples in a Leaf**: The minimum number of samples required to be at a leaf node. A split point at any depth will only be considered if it leaves at least `Minimum Number of Samples in a Leaf` training samples in each of the left and right branches. This may have the effect of smoothing the model, especially in regression. While `Minimum Number of Samples to Split` can create arbitrarily small leaves, `Minimum Number of Samples in a Leaf` guarantees that each leaf has a minimum size, avoiding low-variance, over-fit leaf nodes in regression problems. - Available Options : `sqrt(n)`, `log2(n)`, `n` 8. **Number of Features**: The number of features to consider when looking for the best split. 9. **Class Weights**: Weights associated with classes. If weights are not given, all classes are supposed to have weight one. Note that the class labels are considered in lexicographical order and the number of Class Weights should match number of labels. 10. **Seed**: Random seed. Use the same seed in order to reproduce the same results. 11. **Group By**: Columns to group by. ### Python #### USAGE ``` random_forest_classification_train(table, feature_cols, label_col, n_estimators=10, criterion='gini', max_depth=None, min_samples_split=2, min_samples_leaf=1, min_weight_fraction_leaf=0, max_features='sqrt', max_leaf_nodes=None, min_impurity_decrease=0, class_weight=None, random_state=None, group_by=None) ``` #### INPUT 1. **table***: (Table) Training data in a Table. It must contain at least one column for labels. #### OUTPUT 1. **model**: (Model) Random Forest Classification model #### PARAMETER 1. **feature_cols***: Feature column names. Only values in numeric type are possible. * Type: *list[str]* 2. **label_col***: The column designated for the labels of data. The column should contain categorical type values as it is for classification. * Type: *str* 3. **n_estimators**: Controls the number of trees in the final model. If 1, then no bootstrapping is used. If > 1, then bootstrapping will be performed. Usually the more trees, the higher accuracy. However, both the training and prediction time also grows linearly in the number of trees. * Type: *int* * Default / Range: 10 (value >= 1) 4. **criterion**: The function to measure the quality of a split. * Type: *str* * Default / Range: gini ( gini | entropy ) 5. **max_depth**: The maximum depth of the tree. It restricts the depth of each individual tree to prevent overfitting. If None, then nodes are expanded until all leaves are pure or until all leaves contain less than `min_samples_split`. * Default / Range: (value >= 1) 6. **min_samples_split**: The minimum number of samples required to split an internal node. A very small number will usually mean the tree will overfit, whereas a large number will prevent the tree from learning the data. * Type: *int* * Default / Range: 2 (value >= 2) 7. **min_samples_leaf**: The minimum number of samples required to be at a leaf node. A split point at any depth will only be considered if it leaves at least `min_samples_leaf` training samples in each of the left and right branches. This may have the effect of smoothing the model, especially in regression. While `min_samples_split` can create arbitrarily small leaves, `min_samples_leaf` guarantees that each leaf has a minimum size, avoiding low-variance, over-fit leaf nodes in regression problems. * Type: *int* * Default / Range: 1 (value >= 1) 8. **min_weight_fraction_leaf**: The minimum weighted fraction of the sum total of weights (of all the input samples) required to be at a leaf node. Samples have equal weight when sample_weight is not provided. * Type: *float* * Default / Range: 0.0 (0.0 <= value <= 0.5) 9. **max_features**: The number of features to consider when looking for the best split. If `None`, then Max Features is the number of features used in model training. * Type: *str* * Default / Range: sqrt ( sqrt | log2 | n ) 10. **max_leaf_nodes**: Grow a tree with this value in best-first fashion. Best nodes are defined as relative reduction in impurity. If None then unlimited number of leaf nodes. * Type: *int* * Default / Range: (value >= 1) 11. **min_impurity_decrease**: A node will be split if this split induces a decrease of the impurity greater than or equal to this value. * Type: *float* * Default / Range: 0.0 (value >= 0.0) 12. **class_weight**: Weights associated with classes. If weights are not given, all classes are supposed to have weight one. Note that the class labels are considered in lexicographical order and the number of Class Weights should match number of labels. * Type: _dict_ or _list_[_dict_] 13. **random_state**: Random seed. Use the same seed in order to reproduce the same results. * Type: *int* 14. **group_by**: Columns to group by. * Type: _list_[_str_] ## Example ### VA **[Sample Model]**
In this tutorial workflow, sample_iris data is used to train a random forest classification. The generated model is afterward applied to a test data set to predict the class of _species_, by using Random Forest Classification Predict function. The parameter settings used in the function are shown below. ++Parameters++ 1. **Feature Columns*** : sepal_length, sepal_width 2. **Label Column*** : species 3. **Feature Selection Criterion** : Gini Impurity 4. **Maximum Depth** : None 5. **Minimum Number of Samples to Split** : 2 6. **Minimum Number of Samples in a Leaf** : 1 7. **Number of Features** : sqrt(n) 8. **Class Weights** : None 9. **Seed** : None 10. **Group by** : None ### Python ``` from brightics.function.classification import random_forest_classification_train input_table = inputs[0] result = random_forest_classification_train(table=input_table, feature_cols=["sepal_length", "sepal_width"], label_col="species", criterion='gini', max_depth=None, min_samples_split=2, min_samples_leaf=1, min_weight_fraction_leaf=0, max_features='sqrt', max_leaf_nodes=None, min_impurity_decrease=0, class_weight=None, random_state=None, group_by=None) output = result["model"] ```
In this python script, sample_iris data is used to train a random forest classification. The generated model can be applied to a test data set to predict the class of _species_, by using Random Forest Classification Predict function.
